          definition: "Fiscal policy is the use of government spending (G) and taxation (T) to influence economic activity. A budget deficit (G > T) is expansionary; a budget surplus (T > G) is contractionary. Its objectives are to (1) influence the level of economic activity and aggregate demand, (2) redistribute wealth and income among segments of the population, and (3) allocate resources among economic agents and sectors. Discretionary fiscal policy is deliberate action to stabilize the economy; automatic stabilizers are built-in devices (e.g., unemployment benefits, progressive taxes) triggered by the state of the economy.",
